    <worksheet margin="1in" bottom="1.25in" xml:id="ws-impint">
      <title>Worksheet for Section 6.6</title>

      <objectives>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the definition of convergence to determine whether an improper integral converges.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p> Use the <m>p</m>-test to determine whether an improper integral converges. </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Use the comparison test to decide whether an improper integral converges.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Estimate the error in approximating a definite integral.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </objectives>

      <exercisegroup>
        <title>Evaluating improper integrals</title>


        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_1^\infty \frac{dx}{x^{1.001}}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <p> We have <me>\begin{split}
                  \int_1^\infty \frac{dx}{x^{1.001}}
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \int_1^t x^{-1.001}\,dx \\
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \left.\frac{x^{-0.001}}{-0.001}\right|_1^t \\
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \frac{1-t^{-0.001}}{0.001}\\
                  &amp;= \frac{1-0}{0.001} = 1000
                  \end{split}</me>
              </p>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_1^\infty\frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <p> To find <m>\int \frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx</m>, substitute <m>u=\ln x</m> and <m>
                du=\frac{1}{x}\,dx</m>. <me>\begin{split}
                  \int_1^\infty\frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \int_1^t\frac{\ln x}{x}\,dx \\
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \int_0^{\ln t} u\,du \\
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \left.\frac{u^2}{2}\right|_0^{\ln t} \\
                  &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \left.\frac{(\ln t)^2}{2}\right|_0^{\ln t} = \infty
                \end{split}</me> The integral diverges. </p>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_2^\infty\frac{2\,dx}{x^2 - 1}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> The partial fraction decomposition of <m>\frac{2}{x^2-1}</m> is <me>\frac{2}{x^2-1}
                = \frac{1}{x-1} - \frac{1}{x+1}</me> Therefore, <me>\begin{split}
              \int_2^\infty\frac{2\,dx}{x^2 - 1}
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \int_2^t \left(\frac{1}{x-1} - \frac{1}{x+1}\right)\,dx
                \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \left[\ln|x-1| - \ln|x+1|\right]_2^t \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \ln\left|\frac{x-1}{x+1}\right|^t_2 \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to\infty} \left(\ln\frac{t-1}{t+1} -\ln\frac{1}{3}\right)= \ln 3
              \end{split}</me>
            </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_0^4 \frac{dx}{\sqrt{4-x}}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> We have <me>\begin{split}
                \int_0^4 \frac{dx}{\sqrt{4-x}}
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to4^-}\int_0^t (4-x)^{-1/2}\,dx \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to4^-}\left[ -2(4-x)^{1/2}\right]_0^t \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to4^-}\left[ 2\sqrt{4-x}\right]_t^0 \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to4^-}\left[ 2\sqrt{4}-2\sqrt{4-t}\right] = 4
                \end{split}</me> The integral converges to <m>4</m>. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi/2} \sec \theta\,d\theta</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p>
              <me>\begin{split}
                \int_0^{\pi/2} \sec \theta\,d\theta
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to \pi/2^-} \int_0^{t} \sec \theta\,d\theta \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to \pi/2^-} \left[\ln|\sec\theta + \tan\theta|\right]_0^{t} \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to \pi/2^-} \ln|\sec t + \tan t | = \infty
                \end{split}</me> The integral diverges. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

      </exercisegroup>

      <exercisegroup>
        <title>Testing for convergence</title>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            You can either try to evaluate the integral directly or use the comparison test.
          </p>
        </introduction>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_1^\infty \frac{1}{2x^2 + 3x+ 4} \,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> Let <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{2x^2 + 3x+ 4}</m> and <m>g(x) = \frac{1}{2x^2+3x+4}</m>.
              Notice that <m>0 \leq f(x) \leq g(x)</m> for all <m>x \geq 0</m>, since <m>2x^2 +
                3x+4 \geq x^2</m>. Also, <m>\int_1^\infty g(x)\,dx</m> converges by the <m>p</m>-test
              (<m>p=2&gt;1</m>). So <m>\int_1^\infty f(x)\,dx</m> converges by the comparison test. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi/2} \cot \theta\,d\theta</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> (Direct)We have <me>\int \cot\theta\,d\theta = \int
              \frac{\cos\theta}{\sin\theta}\,d\theta
                = \ln|\sin\theta|+C</me> So <me>\begin{split}
                \int_0^{\pi/2} \cot \theta\,d\theta
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to 0^+} \left[\ln|\sin\theta|\right]^{\pi/2}_t \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to 0^+} \left[\ln|\sin t|\ln|\sin(\pi/2)|-\ln|\sin t|\right] \\
                &amp;= \lim_{t\to 0^+} \left(-\ln|\sin t|\right) \\
                &amp;= \lim_{u\to 0^+} \left(-\ln u \right) = \infty
                \end{split}</me> So the integral diverges. </p>
            <p>(With the comparison test) On the interval <m>[0,\pi/4]</m>, <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}
              &lt; \cos \theta &lt; 1</m> and <m>0 &lt; \sin \theta &lt; x</m>. So on this interval <me>\cot\theta
              = \frac{\cos x}{\sin x} &gt; \frac{1/\sqrt{2}}{x}</me> Now <m>\int_0^{\pi/4}
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{2} x}\,dx</m> diverges by the <m>p</m>-test, so <m>\int_0^\frac{\pi}{4}
              \cot \theta\,d\theta</m> diverges by the comparison test. This means <m>\int_0^\frac{\pi}{2}
              \cot \theta\,d\theta</m> also diverges. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_3^\infty \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-3}}\,dx</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> Let <m>f(x) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-3}}</m> and <m>g(x) = \frac{1}{x}</m>. If <m>x
                &gt; 3</m>, we have <me>\begin{gathered}
                x^2 - 3 &lt; x^2 \\
                \implies \sqrt{x^2-3} &lt; \sqrt{x^2} = x \\
                \implies \frac{1}{\sqrt{x^2-3}} &gt; \frac{1}{x}
                \end{gathered}</me> Therefore <m>g(x) &lt; f(x)</m> for all <m>x &gt; 3</m>. Also, <m>\int_3^\infty
              g(x)\,dx</m> diverges by the <m>p</m>-test (<m>p=1</m>). So <m>\int_3^\infty
                f(x)\,dx</m> diverges by the comparison test. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>

        <exercise workspace="2in">
          <statement>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle\int_0^\pi \frac{\sin \theta\,d\theta}{\sqrt{\pi - \theta}}</m>
            </p>
          </statement>
          <solution>
            <p> The discontinuity is at <m>\theta = \pi</m>. For simplicity, substitute <m>\phi =
                \pi - \theta</m>, <m>d\phi = -d\theta</m>. Then <me>\begin{split}
                \int_0^\pi \frac{\sin \theta\,d\theta}{\sqrt{\pi - \theta}}
                &amp;= - \int_\pi^0 \frac{\Sin{\pi-\phi}}{\sqrt{\phi}}\,d\phi \\
                &amp;= \int_0^\pi \frac{\Sin{\pi-\phi}}{\sqrt{\phi}}\,d\phi \\
                &amp;= \int_0^\pi \frac{\Sin{\phi}}{\sqrt{\phi}}\,d\phi \\
                \end{split}</me> Now <m>0 \leq \Sin{\phi} \leq 1</m> for all <m>\phi</m> in <m>
              [0,\pi]</m>. So we may compare the integrand to <m>\frac{1}{\sqrt{\phi}}=\phi^{-1/2}</m>
              : <me>\frac{\Sin{\phi}}{\sqrt{\phi}} \leq \frac{1}{\sqrt{\phi}}</me> The integral <m>\int_0^\pi
              \frac{1}{\sqrt{\phi}}\,d\phi</m> converges by the <m>p</m>-test (<m>p=1/2 &lt; 1</m>).
              So the given integral converges by the comparison test. </p>
            <p>
              <url href="https://shorturl.at/wJCQn">WolframAlpha</url> says the integral converges
              to approximately <m>1.78966</m>. </p>
          </solution>
        </exercise>
      </exercisegroup>


